{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"12bd469f-cee1-41fc-8a3c-6d1bb258f6ef","content":"In .NET MAUI, use the **lifecycle event mappings** on `MauiAppBuilder`. In your `MauiProgram.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity =>\n        {\n            // runs on Android OnPause\n        })\n        .OnStop(activity =>\n        {\n            // runs on Android OnStop\n        }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app =>\n        {\n            // runs on iOS DidEnterBackground\n        }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` at the top.\n- Platform blocks are guarded with `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives.\n- Each platform exposes its native lifecycle names (e.g., `OnResume`, `WillTerminate`, etc.).\n- This approach keeps all lifecycle wiring in one place without needing custom platform code in the `Platforms/` folders.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7825a7dd-4a17-4a1a-abf7-06308323c850","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI — specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI that I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":360,"requestId":"A43A:32D1ED:613FE4F:69ACE2F:69F004DF"},"id":"aebcbe4b-001a-43fd-85e9-1f44e131d430","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:52:56.259Z","parentId":"37e84e6f-af6f-4322-b387-e724a69a95ad"}
